		<item>
		<title>What We Learned at Social Media Week Toronto </title>
		<link>https://brainstation.io/blog/what-we-learned-at-social-media-week-toronto</link>
				<pubDate>Mon, 18 Nov 2019 22:00:09 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[BrainStation]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Social Media Marketing]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Content marketing]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[digital marketing]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Digital Skills]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[influencer marketing]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[marketing strategy]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[social media]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://blog.brainstation.io/?p=10058</guid>
				<description><![CDATA[<p>Social Media Week brought together a wide range of marketing professionals and experts. Let’s take a closer look at some of the things we learned this year. </p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://brainstation.io/blog/what-we-learned-at-social-media-week-toronto">What We Learned at Social Media Week Toronto </a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://brainstation.io/blog">BrainStation® Blog</a>.</p>
]]></description>
								<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Social Media Week (SMW) 2019 held its Toronto conference last week, and the global event brought together a wide range of marketing professionals and experts. Attendees were eager to explore the impact of social media on the digital and social landscape. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Throughout the four-day conference, one theme was abundantly clear: Be authentic! </span></p>
<p><a href="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smw2.jpeg"><img class="size-full wp-image-10059 aligncenter" src="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smw2.jpeg" alt="" width="680" height="510" srcset="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smw2.jpeg 680w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smw2-300x225.jpeg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /></a></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">We’ve heard this message before, but despite these warnings, it’s easy for Marketers to fall into the trap of producing conversion-centric content. Panelists shared their advice for creating value-based ads that both engage and inspire. They also discussed the importance of creating authentic relationships with your audience. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Let’s take a closer look at some of the things we learned at SMW 2019.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">(Value-Based) Content is King</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">As Jeff Goldnebert of Abacus Agency put it, “you can’t out-perform bad creative.” The experts and panelists from SMW repeatedly reminded us that noteworthy advertising content tends to be values-based (in that it says something about the company’s greater ethos), with campaigns that tell a relatable story. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">When it came to setting standards for content production, both Blue Ant Plus and Pinterest had similar filters with which to gauge the quality of their content. </span></p>
<p><b>Blue Ant Plus aims to produce content that is: </b></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Relatable</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Novel</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Simple</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Filled with tension</span></li>
</ul>
<p><b>Pinterest content aims to be: </b></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Beautiful</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Novel</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Positive</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Attainable</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Active </span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Essentially, both companies stress the importance of producing attention-grabbing ads that tap into people’s real emotions with inspiring, authentic stories. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Blue Ant Plus brought up iconic examples like Nike and Patagonia that tug on heartstrings. Or, as Pinterest likes to say, inspires rather than interrupts. </span></p>
<p><a href="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smwnike.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-10060 size-full" src="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smwnike-e1574112364240.jpg" alt="Nike Ad: Believe in something. Even if it means sacrificing everything." width="752" height="434" srcset="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smwnike-e1574112364240.jpg 752w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smwnike-e1574112364240-300x173.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 752px) 100vw, 752px" /></a></p>
<p><a href="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smwpatagonia.jpg"><img class="alignleft wp-image-10061 size-large" src="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smwpatagonia-1024x576.jpg" alt="Patagonia Ad: Why Patagonia is Fighting for Public Lands: two people look over at national monument" width="1024" height="576" srcset="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smwpatagonia-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smwpatagonia-300x169.jpg 300w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smwpatagonia-768x432.jpg 768w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smwpatagonia-960x540.jpg 960w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/smwpatagonia.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Rise of the Micro-Influencer</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Steve Bartlett, the CEO of Social Chain, A media company and agency, reiterated the importance of inspirational content with a cautionary tale about influencer marketing. Their agency’s research illustrated the vast number of influencer accounts propped up by fake followers; inconsistent influencers who will promote whatever they’re paid to share; and celebrities who are bulking up their like counts with fake accounts. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">It’s no wonder trust is on the decline. Bartlett then further illustrated the point, revealing that a large portion of his conent engagement comes from his podcast diary. Why? Because he’s revealing his true self. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sarah Feldman of Endy also emphasized the importance of finding authentic ambassadors. Endy ensures that their ambassadors have used their product and genuinely improved their sleep because of it, which gives their work for the company a layer of believability and trust, ultimately helping the company develop long-term relationships with its customers. </span></p>
<p><a href="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/endyjannarden.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-10064 size-large" src="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/endyjannarden-1024x576.jpg" alt="Endy mattress ad Jann Arden laying on mattress" width="1024" height="576" srcset="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/endyjannarden-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/endyjannarden-300x169.jpg 300w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/endyjannarden-768x432.jpg 768w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/endyjannarden-960x540.jpg 960w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/endyjannarden.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">To capture some of that authenticity, companies have started focusing on “micro-influencers,” or as Neil Mohan, the Creative Agency Partner at Facebook Canada calls them, “creators.” Micro-influencers have between 1,000 to 1,000,000 followers and are often interested in a specific niche (think foodies, travel junkies, fashionistas, and fitness fanatics). This specialization tends to lead to a deeper, more personal connection with their audiences, with higher engagement. In fact, research has shown that influencers with 1,000 followers generated 85 percent higher engagement than those with 100,000 followers. </span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">Engagement Has to Be Real</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Engaging with your customers should be real as well. Who hasn’t had a frustrating experience with a bot? </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Toronto-based jewelry brand Mejuri was insistent that they create real relationships with their Instagram community. Their social team is made up of members that are actively engaged with and listening to the community to ensure that their interactions come across as genuine. They also don’t want to miss any crucial opportunities for personal interaction or engagement. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Carre Ohem, Social Media Manager from The Gist echoed this sentiment and suggested a series of questions that can help you figure out if your social content will have the kind of reaction you’re looking for. Does the post make you feel something when you’re creating it? Is it funny, sad, or relevant? </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If not, question why you’re posting it and whether it will elicit a real response from your audience. </span></p>
<p>&#8212;</p>
<p><em>Inspired by the latest Social Media Week? Take a look at our <a href="https://brainstation.io/course/social-media-marketing?utm_source=Blog&amp;utm_medium=BRNSTNBlog&amp;utm_campaign=course_SocialMediaMarketing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" data-wplink-edit="true">Social Media Marketing Certificate Courses</a>. </em></p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://brainstation.io/blog/what-we-learned-at-social-media-week-toronto">What We Learned at Social Media Week Toronto </a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://brainstation.io/blog">BrainStation® Blog</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
										</item>
		<item>
		<title>9 Sessions Not to Miss at Social Media Week Toronto 2019</title>
		<link>https://brainstation.io/blog/8-sessions-not-to-miss-at-social-media-week-toronto-2019</link>
				<pubDate>Fri, 08 Nov 2019 16:16:01 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[BrainStation]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Social Media Marketing]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Social media week Toronto]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://blog.brainstation.io/?p=10010</guid>
				<description><![CDATA[<p>The four-day event features more than 40 speakers⁠, with a number of leading social media marketing experts, influencers, and brands. </p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://brainstation.io/blog/8-sessions-not-to-miss-at-social-media-week-toronto-2019">9 Sessions Not to Miss at Social Media Week Toronto 2019</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://brainstation.io/blog">BrainStation® Blog</a>.</p>
]]></description>
								<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Social Media Week Toronto 2019 (#SMWTO 2019) is kicking off next week, and the four-day event features more than 40 speakers⁠ this year, with a number of leading social media marketing experts, influencers, and brands. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are nine sessions you won’t want to miss.  </span></p>
<h3><b>How to Produce for Ad Resistant Eyeballs</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Nov 12, 2019, 11:55 AM – Hosted By Blue Ant Plus</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">In this session, the team from social content agency Blue Ant Plus will explore everything they’ve learned about what makes a piece of branded content work on social media. </span></h3>
<p></span></p>
<h3><b>The End of Marketing: Humanizing Your Brand in the Age of Social Media and AI</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Nov 12, 2019, 9:20 AM – Hosted By Gil Media Co.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Carlos Gil, the author of </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">The End of Marketing: Humanizing Your Brand in the Age of Social Media and AI</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;">, will dive into how to put the ‘social’ back into social media and claim brand relevancy in a world where consumers want to be engaged.</span></p>
<h3><b>Champion Brand Partnerships: Riding the Raptors Wave to Victory </b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Nov 12, 2019, 3:50 PM – Hosted By Rakuten.ca</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Leaders from McDonald’s, Tangerine Bank, and Sun Life discuss their experience partnering with the NBA and the Raptors during the team’s championship victory in 2019. </span></p>
<h3><b>The Pros Guide to TikTok: A New Era of Video Marketing</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Nov 13, 2019, 3:30 PM  – Hosted By TikTok</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Have you heard? TikTok is the latest thing and the platform’s popularity continues to grow. In this session, TikTok influencer Eric Struk will explore the best ways to leverage the platform, and what marketing approaches resonate with Gen Z. </span></p>
<h3><b>Challenge Accepted: Engagement Strategies that Drive ROI</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Nov 13, 2019, 11:30 AM – Hosted By Pinch Social</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Three fast-growing, Toronto-based brands (Knix, Mejuri, and Endy) make up the panel at this session, which takes a closer look at effective community engagement strategies. </span></p>
<h3><b>Twitter Canada: Win Big With Launches  </b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Nov 13, 2019, 1:15 PM – Hosted By Twitter Canada</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In this session, Michelle Slater, Twitter’s Head of Business Marketing, will be revealing new research and lifting the veil on what every brand needs for a successful launch. </span></p>
<h3><b>VICE Canada – The World Is Young: Capturing the Attention of Today’s Youth </b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Nov 14, 2019, 9:45 AM – Hosted By VICE Canada</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Amy Davies, Vice Canada’s Vice President, Client Strategy and Creative will explore how the workplace and purchasing trends are changing, and how media and brands are playing a role. </span></p>
<h3><b>Deepfake, Data, and Robots, Oh My: The Future of AI &amp; Social Media</b></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Nov 14, 2019, 3:15 PM &#8211; Hosted By Pinch Social</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Martin Waxman, CMO at Spin Sucks and social media professor, will explore artificial intelligence, deep learning, and the rise of the smart machine. </span></p>
<p><strong>Paid Social in 2020: What Marketers Need to Know</strong></p>
<p>Nov 14, 2019: 6:30 PM &#8211; Hosted by <a href="https://brainstation.io/events/toronto" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BrainStation</a></p>
<p>This RSVP-only exclusive event can&#8217;t be missed! Speakers from Facebook, AdParlor, Twitter, and Shopify will talk about the paid social trends and best practices.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.socialmediaweektoronto.com/"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Social Media Week Toronto 2019</span></i></a><i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> runs from November 12 to 15 at numerous locations across the city. </span></i></p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://brainstation.io/blog/8-sessions-not-to-miss-at-social-media-week-toronto-2019">9 Sessions Not to Miss at Social Media Week Toronto 2019</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://brainstation.io/blog">BrainStation® Blog</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
